description:
For the linting and the pipeline visualization, we need to be able to get the yaml CI config validated data structure through graphQL. Currently, we can get this data by passing an `ID` to the pipeline field and get all their jobs and needs, etc. But what we want is to be able to pass the content of a `ci config file` and get that data "linted" and get the response back with the data structure mentioned below:

```ruby
{
  stages: [
    {
      name: "test",
      groups: [
        {
          name: "jest",
          size: 2,
          jobs: [
            { name: "jest 1/2" },
            { name: "jest 2/2" },
          ],
        },
        { 
          name: "rspec",
          size: 1,
          jobs: [
            { name: "rspec" }
          ]
        },
      ]
    },
    {
      name: "post-test",
      groups: [
        {
          name: "jest-coverage"
          size: 1,
          jobs: [
            { name: "jest-coverage", needs: ["jest"] }
          ]
        },
        { ... }
      ]
    },
  ]
}

```

To note that this data structure, if possible, should parse the entire stages and jobs array **with every includes** so that the returned response has all the jobs of the project and not just those present in the current CI config that was linted.

The issue data stored in Elasticsearch will now contain `access_level` field to determine permissions.

This should allow global scoped searches to use the `access_level` field instead of doing a join on the parent field.

We expect this to reduce the complexity and improve performance.

